{
  "doc_id": "58655",
  "text": "The extent of tumor heterogeneity confounds our understanding of tumor evolution and clinical progression and our ability to restrain treatment resistance and design effective cancer-therapeutic interventions. Tumor heterogeneity is beginning to be appreciated as the major obstacle to effective treatment and personalized medicine [CITATION_1] . Although heterogeneity is assumed to arise from diverse cell types recruited to the tumor and from the differential integration of genetic, epigenetic, and microenvironmental influences among the cancer cells themselves [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , the ultimate mechanisms responsible for the emergence of tumor heterogeneity remain poorly understood and controversial. The current models explaining inter-and intra-tumoral diversity are the clonal evolution and cancer stem cell (CSC) hypotheses [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
